The investigation included:

1. House-to-house hygiene education through 161,370 meetings with families in affected communities;
2. Periodic water samples for cholera testing;
3. Chlorination of 86,832 shallow wells in residential areas;
4. House-to-house distribution of 1,139,694 chlorine tablets and liquid chlorine in the areas most affected by the outbreak;
5. House-to-house distribution of 98,000 ORS packets;
6. Information, education and communication campaigns on personal hygiene and use of ORS for the Kabul residents most affected, including distribution of 42,000 posters, 60,000 leaflets, 400 flipcharts and 200 banners.

The Afghan Ministry of Public Health, partner agencies, and the system established to provide the Basic Package of Health Services took immediate actions to mitigate the effects of the contamination by:

1. House-to-house hygiene education through 161,370 meetings with families in affected communities;
2. Periodic water samples for cholera testing;
3. Chlorination of 86,832 shallow wells in residential areas;
4. House-to-house distribution of 1,139,694 chlorine tablets and liquid chlorine in the areas most affected by the outbreak;
5. House-to-house distribution of 98,000 ORS packets;
6. Information, education and communication campaigns on personal hygiene and use of ORS for the Kabul residents most affected, including distribution of 42,000 posters, 60,000 leaflets, 400 flipcharts and 200 banners.

The initial actions taken to investigate or inspect the event included:

1. Media appeals;
2. Contacting surrounding physicians, hospitals, and laboratories;
3. Conducting a household survey;
4. Collecting stool specimens from newly recognized cases of bloody or severe diarrhea;
5. Inspecting the municipal water and sewage system;
6. Evaluating possible cross-connections between the water and sewer systems;
7. Using water-system flow data and household locations of all known cases of bloody diarrhea inside the city to create a computer model.

The age demographics of the individuals mentioned in the text are as follows:

* 57% (n=187/329) of ill persons were female, including four who were pregnant;
* The median age of ill persons was 37 years (range: 0-98 years).
